cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.GT, cs.SI. 

The paper deals with a problem in computational geometry (finding a tour of points in Euclidean space), which suggests that it could belong to cs.CG (Computational Geometry) or cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The use of approximation algorithms and polynomial-time algorithms suggests that it could also belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) or cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). Finally, the applications in manufacturing and medical imaging suggest that it could belong to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
